reviewText: Thanks to a friend of mine finally cleaning out his garage, I was given a bunch of old VHS tapes including this one which was WCW's Uncensored '98.  The problems within the nWo between Savage & Hogan got so bad after Savage cost Hogan the WCW Championship that Savage began to have allies within WCW such as Sting, Scott Steiner had turned on his brother Rick to join the nWo, and the nWo made it clear that they were out to get Bret Hart after Hogan felt like he cost him his championship back at Starrcade.WCW Television Champion Booker T vs. Eddie Guerrero - Chavo Guerrero Jr. was in Eddie's corner due to losing a match causing him to be Eddie's "slave."  Booker was in control during the first half of the match with his power advantage using moves like the press slam before Eddie was able to gain an advantage with a dropkick to Eddie's knee during an attempt at a scissors kick & continued to work over the knee which kept having an effect on Booker throughout the match.  This went back & forth in what turned out to be a very competitive match with the story of Chavo refusing to help Eddie when requested allowing Booker to gain the victory.Juventud Guerrera vs. Konnan - Konnan felt that Juventud was a disgrace to the luchadors due to him losing his mask against Mysterio the previous month setting up this match.  Konnan had a clear weight advantage over Juventud & used that against but this was all about pushing Juvi's new "no surrender" attitude as he refused to give up & eventually overcame the odds with a rollup for the wni.WCW Crusierweight Champion Chris Jericho vs. Dean Malenko - For weeks leading up to this match, Jericho mocked Dean Malenko to the point where he made up his own his monicker of being "The Man Of 1,004 Holds" to the point where he had the #1,004 on his outfit.  Malenko outwrestled Jericho early to the point where he almost walked out of the match leading Dean to break the count.  They traded momentum throughout the match with Jericho attempting backbreaker & chinlock submissions while Malenko at one point was able to reverse an attempted frankensteiner off the top rope into his famous top rope gutbuster.  Jericho was eventually able to catch Malenko in the Liontamer for the submission victory causing Gene Okerland afterwords to call Malenko out on the fact that he's lost all his attempts to regain the Crusierweight Championship in the past few months causing Malenko just declare he was going "home."Lex Luger vs. Scott Steiner - This match lasted less than 5 minutes & wasn't too much to make any note of past the fact that we got a small physical confrontation between Rick & Scott Steiner during & after the match.WCW United States Champion Dallas Page vs. Chris Benoit vs. Raven - This was a triple threat match where all three men were legal at the same time with the first person to score the fall wins the match but the bonus twist here is that this was held under Raven's rules which made this a glorified No Disqualification Match.  Both men started off with a triple set of moves such as a 3 way headlock only for all three men to fall to the floor on the third attempt with DDP being thrown into the steps.  This was pretty wild with all three men brawling from the ring to the stage with weapons from a trash can to crutches to the kitchen sing with DDP being through through the electric Uncensored sign at one point.  When they all got back to the ring, it was a string a 3 way moves such as a sleeper hold, jaw breaker, and german suplex.  Complete with the "Use My Sign" spot & a Diamond Cutter off the top rope through a table, this was one of WCW's best "hardcore" matches.Giant vs. Kevin Nash - Giant was out for revenge for his injured neck after the powerbomb at Souled Out & at his request, the powerbomb was legal to use in this match.  Giant came out wearing a neck brace & flattened Nash early with a clothesline followed by a running elbow drop early on.  Nash was able to regain control by working over his neck with moves like the sleeper & chokes on the second rope before eventually removing the neck brace.  Giant regained his momentum & was about to payback Nash with his own powerbomb before Brian Adams got involved using a baseball bat which was eventually broken over Giant.  This went a little over 5 mins. but was more about pushing the story between these two than anything else.Bret Hart vs. Curt Hennig - This was from their short feud in WCW where Bret Hart has issues with the nWo so Curt Hennig took on the task of taking out Bret Hart. Hennig did focus on Bret's knee but it was interesting to hear how Mike Tenay referenced to their past history without actually mentioning WWE by name. As was typical with the nWo at that time, Rick Rude did get involved & delivered the first Rude Awakening in years. This was a good encounter as they never had a bad match but they've had much better.[Life & Times Of Mr. Perfect]WCW Champion Sting vs. Scott Hall - Hall, with Dusty Rhodes in his corner, won the World War 3 Battle Royal back in November to earn this title shot.  Sting was in control early as Hall had a moment to gain momentum but lost it quickly when he decided to showboat instead of go for the win.  This match went back & forth with Dusty had to keep getting involved various time in order for Hall to get an advantage, including dropping his bionic elbow at one point, but he payed for on the third attempt allowing Sting to get the win in what was a nice match.Steel Cage Match: Randy Savage vs. Hollywood Hogan - Hogan was in control in the first half of this match dominating Savage while using whatever was near him to use against Savage including his weight belt but Savage was able to regain control when Hogan missed his legdrop causing Savage to repay Hogan for his use of the weight belt earlier.  The cage played a heavy factor here as Savage took hard bumps into it such as being backdropped into it & being rammed headfirst into it while Savage also used it to his advantage to drop a double axe-handle off the top of the cage onto Hogan.  Both men eventually fought out of the cage for a moment but the match really broke down when Savage went to the top of the cage to hit the elbow before The Disciple came out to protect Hogan causing Sting (who had been allies with Savage for the past few weeks) to come down to stand by Savage's side...only for Savage to turn on him & walk out of the cage leaving everyone, including Hogan, confused.  It was a nice match but again, was more about continuing to push their story.In the end, this was mostly a "filler" WCW PPV as a majority of the matches here were only to continue to push the feuds between all the men involved but did get get some good action (the title matches along with Bret/Hennig) overall so it's an event that I would check out in the future.

reviewText: Ok, I just watched this video and it's 4 years old. I was bored at my work, so, I popped it in. First off, I didn't have any expectations in this title at all. It's a free video, what do I have to lose?As I'm sitting there watching this pay per view, I realized how great WCW was or could have been. Yes, this pay-per-view was missing Goldberg, but, he wasn't needed to make this very entertaining and great pay-per-view. every match was exciting and worth watching again and again. The suprise was the fact that there were no tag team matches. I enjoy tag matches, but, not as much as singles.the sleeper match of the night was Konnan vs. Juventud Guerrera. Konnan showed so many submission maneuvers, I ended up losing count. He used many variations and he used many high impact moves that will make you say 'DAMN!'but, the best match of the night was definately Chris Jericho vs. Dean Malenko. the outcome alone was worth the entire match alone. Mean Gene then came down and pretty much berated Malenko before Malenko pretty much said he quit and walked out.but, the runner-up as best match of the night..the Triple Threat U.S. title match. DDP vs. Raven vs. Chris Benoit. a good finish in this match, even though it was botched.there were other stand out matches on this card alone that could be easily known as the best matches of the night. WCW Championship match: Sting(c) vs. Scott Hall, TV Championship: Booker T(c) vs. Eddy Guerrero, and Bret Hart vs. Curt Hennig.the only other 3 matches on the card were those of (Steel Cage Match) Hollywood Hogan vs. Macho Man Randy Savage, Lex Luger vs. Scott Steiner and Kevin Nash vs. Giant. i'm not saying these 3 matches were horrible, which they were not. but, compared to the others, these 3 are just at the bottom of the list. but, I enjoyed these matches.but, the pay per view as a whole, this was great and entertaining. highly recommened for those who believe WCW couldn't put together a good solid pay per view and those who just haven't given WCW a chance. and WCW fans, rent this again and again or purchase it, if you can
